033package squidpony.squidmath;
034
035/**
036 * An IDistribution that produces double results with a Gaussian (normal) distribution. This means it has no limits in
037 * any direction, but is much more likely to produce results close to 0. This now uses the Box-Muller Transform (it
038 * previously used the Ziggurat method), which means it relies on trigonometric functions
039 * ({@link NumberTools#sin_(double)} and {@link NumberTools#cos_(double)}, which are approximations), square root and
040 * logarithm calculations, but it only needs to calculate every other number, and it uses a fixed amount of calls to
041 * {@link IRNG#nextDouble()} (for every pair of outputs, it makes two calls to nextDouble()).
042 * <br>
043 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 11/23/2019, rewritten on 7/30/2020.
044 */
045public class GaussianDistribution implements IDistribution {
046    
047    public static final GaussianDistribution instance = new GaussianDistribution();
048    
049    private double cachedNext = 0.0;
050    private boolean needsMore = true;
051    
052    @Override
053    public double nextDouble(IRNG rng) {
054        if(needsMore ^= true)
055            return cachedNext;
056        final double mul = Math.sqrt(-2.0 * Math.log(1.0 - rng.nextDouble()));
057        final double variate = rng.nextDouble();
058        cachedNext = mul * NumberTools.cos_(variate);
059        return mul * NumberTools.sin_(variate);
060    }
061
062    /**
063     * The lower inclusive bound is negative infinity.
064     * @return negative infinity
065     */
066    @Override
067    public double getLowerBound() {
068        return Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY;
069    }
070
071    /**
072     * The upper inclusive bound is infinity.
073     * @return positive infinity
074     */
075    @Override
076    public double getUpperBound() {
077        return Double.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
078    }
